@page
@model IndexModel
@{
    ViewData["Title"] = "Home";
}

<section class="hero-panel">
    <span class="eyebrow">Week 7 Project 03</span>
    <h1>Render server-side HTML fragments with declarative <code>hx-*</code> attributes.</h1>
    <p class="lead">
        This sample demonstrates the HTMX workflow: buttons and forms declare where requests go, where HTML is inserted,
        and how loading indicators appear, without writing page-specific JavaScript.
    </p>
    <div class="action-row">
        <a class="button button-primary" asp-page="/HtmxBoard">Open The HTMX Demo</a>
        <a class="button button-secondary" href="/fragments/notices" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">View A Fragment Response</a>
    </div>
</section>

<section class="card-grid">
    <article class="info-card">
        <h2>What students practise</h2>
        <ul>
            <li>Use <code>hx-get</code>, <code>hx-post</code>, <code>hx-target</code>, and <code>hx-swap</code>.</li>
            <li>Receive HTML fragments from the server instead of JSON.</li>
            <li>Show loading indicators with declarative markup.</li>
            <li>Append or replace content without custom page scripts.</li>
        </ul>
    </article>

    <article class="info-card">
        <h2>Why this project matters</h2>
        <ul>
            <li>The browser behavior stays simple because the HTML describes the request.</li>
            <li>The server controls the rendered markup, which keeps the frontend lighter.</li>
            <li>Students can compare this approach directly with the Fetch API projects.</li>
        </ul>
    </article>
</section>

<section class="info-panel">
    <h2>Suggested walkthrough</h2>
    <ol>
        <li>Load the board and observe that the stats panel fills itself on page load.</li>
        <li>Refresh the notices panel with <code>hx-get</code> and inspect the HTML fragment response.</li>
        <li>Submit a reflection form with <code>hx-post</code> and watch a new feed item append to the top.</li>
        <li>Check the loading indicator to see how request feedback appears without custom page logic.</li>
    </ol>
</section>
